<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-750-263  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 750 263.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  July 3 1989 v3 n27 p19(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FBI shouldn't cave in on crime info data base. (Op-ed inperspective)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zall, Milton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The FBI maintains an automated information system called theNational Crime Information Center which holds about 20 millionrecords concerning the status of wanted or missing persons, stolenproperty and criminal histories.andP;  This data base is utilized byover 64,000 federal, state and local law enforcement agencies.andP;  Itprocesses 750,000 inquiries each day and constitutes an invaluableresource for the law enforcement community.andP;  The NCIC has comeunder criticism recently by civil libertarian organizations suchas the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) and the ComputerProfessionals for Social Responsibility (CPSR).andP;  While the issueof privacy and the concern that the information system may ineffect be used for surveillance purposes, brought up by thesegroups, are important, these concerns should not be allowed toreduce the effectiveness of such an important security tool.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Federal Bureau of InvestigationUnited States. National Crime Information CenterComputer Professionals for Social ResponsibilityAmerican Civil Liberties UnionInformation ServicesLaw EnforcementData SecurityPolicyData Bases.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>